pan></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Consent is normally given </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Queen or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Prince of Wales as Duke of C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ornwall but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they occasionally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> give</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">respect of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">title</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.05pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Queen </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve her </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consent to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">right of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Duchy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of Lancaster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, see </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Annex B.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prince</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nsent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was given </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the House of Lords Bill 1998-99</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in relation to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the rights of the principality of Wales and Earldom of Chester</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, to which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">explicit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reference was made in the Bill.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prince</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s consent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as Prince and Steward of Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">always been rare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and may now have been superseded altogether</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lthough the Scotland Act </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1998 refers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">specifically </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the Prince and Steward of Scotland.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">pecific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">question</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s raised by the Committee</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Committee has invited comments on specific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">questions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> concerning Queen’s and Prince’s Consent.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">response to those questions to which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are in a position to respond</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is given below.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Process</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-31.5pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Questions 1 and 2</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on whether Queen’s or Prince’s Consent is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">required </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">taken </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the first instance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Clerks of Legislation of the two Houses.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The decision is normally straightforward but if there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ere</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> any uncertainty the Clerks of Legislation would examine relevant precedents and, if necessary, consult the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ir respective </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Clerks.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If the decision concerned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a Government Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would not be challenged.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 3</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government’s usual practice is to advise t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he granting of consent even to Bills of which it disapproves.  As </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">May</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> explains “The understanding is that the grant of consent does not imply approval by the Crown or its advisers, but only that the Crown does not intend that, for lack of its consent, Parliament should be debarred from debating such provisions.”</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the Commons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ministers have occasionally declined to seek consent on the ground that a private Member’s Bill was unlikely to be debated.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Queen’s or Prince’s Consent is refused only on the advice of the Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Governments have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">occasionally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">declined to advise the Sovereign to give consent to Bills to which they were opposed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, see</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the debate on the St Asaph and Bangor Dioceses Bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1844.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1868 the Commons </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resorted to a direct request </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to Her Majesty for her consent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by means of an Address.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  Her Majesty agreed to the request.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Established Church</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(Ireland) Bill was sub</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sequently passed by the Commons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Lords took similar action in 1875 in re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gard to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Irish Peerages</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he distinction between the constitutional duty of the Prince of Wales to act on the advice of the Government in respect of his interest and his personal position in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">relation to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a private </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Bill was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> demonstrated in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1970 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Prince of Wales, as Duke of Cornwall, both consented to the Plymouth and South </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">West </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Devon Water Bill and petitioned against it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Counsel appearing before the Committee on the Bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stated:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">he Duchy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> object to the Bill and submit that it should not be allowed to pass into law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">..</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">constitutionally a Private Bill cannot confer powers to acquire compulsorily property belonging to His Royal Highness </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the Prince of Wales in right of H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">is Duchy of Cornwall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">, and in implementation of this constitutional principle clause 49 has been included in the Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">However, the Duchy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">wishes to present its views to Parliament and accordingly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">waives its right</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> under that clause</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">If, after hearing those views and those of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> other Petitioners, Parliament decides that it is in the public interest to authorise the construction of the Swincombe reservoir and associated works, the Duchy would accept that decision and negotiate with the water undertakers for the sale or lease to them of such land and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> interests </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">in the land as may be required for the reservoir and other works.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here could be no similar distinction in relation to a public Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 5</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rivate Members are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inform</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed of the need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to obtain consent as soon as th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">requirement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for consent has been identified by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Clerk of Legislation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  Members are advised to write to the relevant Government Minister who will, in turn, seek </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Queen’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prince’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Consent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the unlikely event of a Member challenging the Clerk of Legislation’s advice, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the Commons </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the final decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on whether consent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s required would be taken by the Speaker.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the Lords, the House itself would be the ultimate authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There have been a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">few occasions on which Queen’s consent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to a Private Member’s Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not been signified</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  The Question could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not be proposed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The impact</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Questions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">1 and 2</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.39pt; padding-left:11.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Queen’s Consent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is obtained </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for matters which affect </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Her</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Majesty’s prerogative or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the hereditary revenues, personal property or personal interests of the Crown or the Duchies of Lancaster or Cornwall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.39pt; padding-left:11.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> wish to consider whether </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the process of signifying</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Queen’s and Prince’s c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onsent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> could be simplified.  At present consent has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be signified personally by a Privy Counsellor in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">House</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ill is to be considered</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he fact that c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onsent has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">obtained</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">instead </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be noted on the Order Paper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(in the Commons, this would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the same way as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">noting the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Queen’s reco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mmendation to a Money Resolution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">That would avoid the possibility of the absence of a Privy Counsellor preventing the question being proposed on a Bill.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.31pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The process could also be made more transparent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At present, unless consent is required to be signified on second reading, Members are unaware that a Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> requires Queen’s or Prince’s consent until after the Bill has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(in the Commons) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">completed its committee stage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or (in the Lords) until the day of Third Reading</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  The requirement for consent could be put o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n the Order Paper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the relevant House </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as soon as the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Bill had</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been printed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Alternatively the Committee may wish to consider whether the distinction between signification of consent on second or third reading is still valid or whether consent should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">instead </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be signified at the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">same stage on every B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  As amendments made in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Committee or on consideration occasionally require Queen’s consent it would be preferable to delay signification of consent until third reading.  That would also mean </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there was more time for private Members to obtain consent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Commons p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rivate Members’ Bills are sometimes printed only days b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">efore second reading and it might</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not be apparent until the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> final version </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s available </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that consent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ould</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">equired.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Question 3</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20.19pt; padding-left:11.26pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Provided the import of Queen’s and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prince’s consent is understood </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and accurately represented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the requirement for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Queen’s or Prince’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consent should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">run </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">no greater risk of politicising the monarchy than does the requirement that Bills passed by both Houses of Parliament </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not become law until they receive Royal Assent.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p sty