es, taken from the Enemy.”  Leave was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">given</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to certain Ministers to pre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are and bring in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Suppression of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Piracy Bill.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Another </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significant event </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in relation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the development of Queen’s c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onsent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">concerned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">St Asaph and Bangor Diocese</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Bill 1844.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  In the Commons the Minister, Sir Robert Peel, said “that if the Speaker should decide that in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ouse of Commons the consent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the Crown</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would be necessary – then,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in that case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> he should not feel it to be consistent with his duty to advise the Crown to consent to it.”</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.96pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A Bill with the same object had been introduced in the House of Lords.</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The issue of whether the House could pass a Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which required the consent of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Crown but for whi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ch no consent had been given wa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s debated at some length.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Viscount Canterbury</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">said he was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sure “that it was the most anxious desire of both Houses of Parliament to preserve intact and inviolate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the prerogatives of the Crown as the privileges of Parliament</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.”</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 4 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">July </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1844 the House of Lords resolved that it be an Instruction to the Committee appointed to inquire </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with respect to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consider whether the Bill for preventing the Union of the Sees of St Asaph and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Bangor belongs to that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> class of Bills for which it has been the Usage to give the Consent of the Crown before passing the House</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and to report generally on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Precedents bearing on the case, including the question of the particular stage of the Bill at which consent has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">usually </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">given.”</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following day </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Chairman reported that such consent was necessary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> On </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">11 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">July</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, during further debate on the Bill, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reference was made to the statement by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Duke of Wellington </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was not the intention of the Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to advise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Crown to give </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assent to the progress of the measure.”</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.96pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 1868 the House agreed to a Motion for an humble Address moved by Gladstone, then on the Opposition side of the House, that “Her Majesty would be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">graciously </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pleased to place at the disposal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of Parliament, Her interest in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e temporalities of the Archbishoprics</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, Bishoprics,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and other Ecclesiastical Dignities and Benefices in Ireland, and in t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e custody thereof”.</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.96pt; padding-left:3.74pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Her Majesty replied:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Relying on the wisdom of My Parliament, I desire that My interest in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">emporalities of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">United Church of England and Ireland, in Ireland, may not stand in the way of the consideration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by Parliament, of any measure relating thereto, that may be introduced in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the present Session.”</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Established </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Church (Ireland) Bill was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">read the first time </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14 May 1868</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and passed on 16</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> June 1868.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ANNEX B</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Queen’s Consent in right of the Duchy of Lancaster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Duchy of Lancaster is Crown Land and Queen’s Consent is required if a Bill affects its interests.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Since 1975 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Queen’s Consent in right of the Duchy of Lancaster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has been</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> signified </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the following Bills and Measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  The dates relate to signification in the House of Commons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Care of Places of Worship Measure, 23 June 1999</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Priests (Ordination of Women) Measure, 29 October 1993</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tenants’ Rights Etc (Scotland), 7 August 1980</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">West Yorkshire Bill [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Lords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">], 22 April 1980</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">County of Merseyside Bill [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Lords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">], 19 February 1980</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Rent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Agriculture</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Bill, 22 July 1976</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">British Transport Docks Bill, 21 June 1976</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">British Transport Docks Bill, 12 June 1974</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Merseyside Metropolitan Railway Bill, 18 March 1975</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_1062965000290"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">For a fuller list see May, 24</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> edition, page 661.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Co-operative and Community Benefit Societies and Credit Unions Bill 2008-09.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">May, 24</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> edition, page 663.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> For example, Bishops (Retirement) Measure and Patronage (Benefices) Measure 1985-86.</span></p><p style="font-size:9pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">See, for example, Business Rate Supplements Bill 2008-09.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Local Democracy, Economic Development and Construction Bill [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Lords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">] 2008-09.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Hunting Bills 2002-03 &amp; 2003-04; Marine and Coastal Access Bill [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Lords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">] 2008-09.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Marine Navigation Aids Bill [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Lords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">] 2009-10.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Because the Duke of Cornwall is the harbour authority for the Scilly Isles.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Crown Charters (Scotland) Bill 1847; Conveyancing and Feudal Reform (Scotland) Bill 1969-70; Prescription and Limitation (Scotland) Bill [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Lords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">] 1972-73; Land Registration (Scotland) Bill [</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Lords</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">] 1978-79. See also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Guidance issued by the Office of the Parliamentary Counsel, Appendix B.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Schedule 3 to the Scotland Act 1998 provides that “The standing orders shall include provision for ensuring that a Bill containing provisions which would, if the Bill were a Bill for an Act of Parliament, require the consent of Her Majesty, the Prince and Steward of Scotland or the Duke of Cornwall shall not pass unless such consent has been signified to the Parliament.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> May, 24</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> edition, page 167.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> For example, Titles (Abolition) Bill, 27 February 1964.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 7 May 1868.  Her Majesty’s reply was received on 12 May 1868.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn15"></a><a href="#_ftnref15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 16 June 1868.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn16"></a><a href="#_ftnref16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> HLJ 107 1875  357; 372-3. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn17"></a><a href="#_ftnref17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> The Bill was subsequently reported without amendment (Preamble not proved).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn18"></a><a href="#_ftnref18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> On second reading of the Military Actions against Iraq (Parliamentary Approval) Bill, 16 April 1999; on third reading of the Pig Husbandry Bill, 3 May 1991.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn19"></a><a href="#_ftnref19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> CJ (1727-32), 242-3.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn20"></a><a href="#_ftnref20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> HC Deb 25 June 1844, vol 75, cols 1352-3.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn21"></a><a href="#_ftnref21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> Sees of St Asaph and Bangor Bill.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn22"></a><a href="#_ftnref22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> HL Deb, 1 July 1844, vol 76, cols 122-132.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn23"></a><a href="#_ftnref23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> HL Deb, 4 July 1844, vol 76, cols 294-6.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn24"></a><a href="#_ftnref24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> HL Deb, 5 July 1844, vol 76, col 422.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn25"></a><a href="#_ftnref25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> HL Deb, 11 July, vol 76, col 591.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn26"></a><a href="#_ftnref26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> 7 May 1868, CJ 123 ,160.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn27"></a><a href="#_ftnref27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:9pt"> 12 May 1868, CJ 123 170.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>